    <h1>Still crav&#xAD;ing cock&#xAD;les?</h1>
    <h2>Check out these five dishes to &#x201C;warm the cock&#xAD;les of your heart&#x201D; and fill your tummy</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200719/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-07-19"><time>2020-07-19</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline">Eu&#xAD;nice Quek Food Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent eu&#xAD;niceq@sph.com.sg&#xD;&#xA;&#x2022;&#xD;&#xA;Fol&#xAD;low Straits Times Food on Face&#xAD;book and In&#xAD;sta&#xAD;gram @strait&#xAD;stimes&#xAD;food</span>
    </section>

    <p>Dur­ing the re­cent gen­eral elec­tion, there was much talk of cock­les and warmed hearts.</p>
    <p>In his thank-you speech af­ter the Work­ers’ Party team won Sengkang GRC, As­so­ci­ate Pro­fes­sor Ja­mus Lim said: “It warms the cock­les of our hearts to be able to work for the peo­ple of Sengkang, and for all Sin­ga­pore­ans.”</p>
    <p>This left many with a ma­jor crav­ing for cock­les, and Sin­ga­pore so­cial me­dia last week­end was filled with a pro­lif­er­a­tion of dishes that fea­tured the ed­i­ble mol­lusc.</p>
    <p>In 2006, the pop­u­lar shell­fish re­ceived a men­tion in Prime Min­is­ter Lee Hsien Loong’s Na­tional Day Rally speech. He said “mee siam mai hum” (mee siam, no cock­les), in­stead of “laksa mai hum” (laksa, no cock­les). The phrase went vi­ral as mee siam is not served with cock­les.</p>
    <p>The Sun­day Times rounds up five dishes that fea­ture cock­les in var­i­ous styles, even a dessert ver­sion.</p>
    <p>MRS PHO COCK­LES What:</p>
    <p>This is a must-or­der side dish when I dine at the ca­sual Viet­namese restau­rant chain.</p>
    <p>The highly raved-about sig­na­ture cock­les are sim­ply stir-fried in lard and gar­lic, and served in their shells. Half the fun is in pris­ing out the meat and ex­tract­ing all the gar­licky good­ness.</p>
    <p>Each por­tion is priced at $14.20 (above). You can get 50 per cent off (till July 31 for de­liv­ery only) when you or­der it with a set meal from its Ran­goon Road out­let.</p>
    <p>Mrs Pho out­lets at B2-29 VivoCity, 1 Har­bourfront Walk;</p>
    <p>221 Ran­goon Road; and 349 Beach Road; open: 11am to 10pm daily</p>
    <p>Is­land­wide de­liv­ery avail­able at or­der.MrsPho.com</p>
    <p>Where: Info: What:</p>
    <p>Laksa is not com­plete with­out cock­les, and the De­pot Road Zhen Shan Mei Laksa’s Bib Gour­mand-rated ver­sion is one of my favourites. Each bowl (left) is priced up­wards of $4 and I sug­gest adding $2.50 for more cock­les. Though small, the cock­les are fresh and plump.</p>
    <p>The only down­side is that the stall has stopped serv­ing laksa in clay­pots – which used to set it apart from oth­ers.</p>
    <p>De­pot Road Zhen Shan Mei Laksa, 01-75 Alexan­dra Vil­lage Food Cen­tre, Block 120 Bukit Merah Lane 1; open: 9am to 3pm, Tues­days to Satur­days, closed on Sun­days and Mon­days</p>
    <p>De­liv­ery avail­able via Food­panda and GrabFood</p>
    <p>Where: Info:</p>
    <p>Where:</p>
    <p>Info:</p>

